{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"85fcf18a-f828-4612-8d8c-7c544a5fd0d4","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for local tools):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — runs `dotnet run` pointing at your `.csproj`.\n- For a **published** build, use `\"command\": \"path/to/MyMcpServer\"` instead.\n- If your server needs environment variables, add an `\"env\": {}` block.\n\nAfter saving, open the Copilot chat panel in agent mode (`@workspace`) — VS Code will auto-start the server and discover its tools.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"37d1ccc4-7472-4700-a172-6c5e2e395f2f","outputTokens":274},"id":"4e418e00-224f-4ffd-8453-653ad3454176","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:47:28.037Z","parentId":"aa1cb447-8b75-4e11-a98c-9a1538cf40a9"}
